{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"981"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/981"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.04,0.02,0.73,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97845"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/981"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"598"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43055"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97845"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with sore breasts five days after a normal vaginal delivery of a healthy baby girl. She reports that her breasts feel hard, swollen, and painful. The pregnancy was uncomplicated. She is G2P2. Her newborn has been feeding approximately 10 times a day and has been passing at least six wet nappies a day, with a steady weight gain since birth weight. She does not take any regular medications and has no significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her breasts appear swollen and engorged. There are no areas of erythema or localised tenderness. The nipples appear normal, with no cracks, bleeding, or apparent infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advise to use a breast pump immediately before a feed","Prophylactic antibiotics for seven days","Oral bromocriptine STAT","Advise hand express small amounts of breastmilk for comfort","Oral domperidone for use PRN"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing breast engorgement, a common condition that typically occurs 3-5 days postpartum when milk production increases rapidly. The clinical picture shows classic signs of engorgement (swollen, hard breasts) without signs of mastitis (no fever, erythema, or localised tenderness).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvise hand express small amounts of breastmilk for comfort\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Hand expression removes just enough milk to relieve discomfort and help the baby latch properly without overstimulating milk production. This gentle approach helps maintain the supply-demand balance while providing relief. Additional supportive measures include frequent feeding, cold compresses between feeds, and gentle massage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvise to use a breast pump immediately before a feed\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as the primary approach for engorgement. Breast pumps provide stronger stimulation than hand expression or infant suckling and can actually worsen oversupply by signaling the body to produce even more milk. This creates a cycle of increased production and engorgement. Pumps should generally be reserved for situations where hand expression is insufficient or when milk needs to be stored.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic antibiotics for seven days\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in this case as there are no signs of infection such as erythema, localised tenderness, or fever. Antibiotics should be reserved for cases of mastitis, which typically presents with a wedge-shaped area of redness, tenderness, and often systemic symptoms including fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral bromocriptine STAT\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate and potentially dangerous. Bromocriptine is a dopamine agonist that suppresses prolactin and thus milk production. It is no longer recommended for lactation suppression due to serious adverse effects including stroke, seizures, myocardial infarction, and psychiatric disturbances. Additionally, this mother is successfully breastfeeding and wishes to continue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral domperidone for use PRN\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in this situation. Domperidone is a dopamine antagonist that increases prolactin levels and thus milk production. It is sometimes used for mothers with insufficient milk supply, but would worsen engorgement in this case of oversupply.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hand expression is the preferred method for relieving breast engorgement as it removes only enough milk for comfort without stimulating increased production.","Breast engorgement typically occurs 3-5 days postpartum when milk production increases rapidly.","Frequent feeding, cold compresses, and gentle massage are non-pharmacological approaches to managing breast engorgement."],"references":["Breast feeding Australia. Too Much Milk.\u00a0 https://www.breastfeeding.asn.au/bf-info/common-concerns%E2%80%93mum/too-much-milk. Accessed 15/09/20"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"981"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T18:07:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T23:26:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"981"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97845"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/598"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Breast engorgement","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-03T14:30:08+09